Fuji-Q Highland dump…

Pretty cool experience taking the kid to one of the top theme parks in Japan - Fuji Q Highland. It was the one thing he was looking forward to most on his first international trip. We almost didn’t make it but ended up going at the perfect time, on a Tuesday. Not too crowded. Rode 3 of the top coasters in the world - a few in the Guinness Book of World Records. Ejanaika was the most modern, Takabisha had the steepest drop and Fujiyama was the most intense. (we rode that 2x) Also got to roam a haunted hospital for an hour. That was intense in a great way! I’ve yet to experience a haunted attraction in the U.S. that compares. All in all, I’m really glad I was able to deliver and take my kid to this place. It puts a bow on our first trip to Japan and I hope he remembers the experience forever. He tells me he wants to initiate travel more anytime he is able so I’ve accomplished my mission of giving him some wanderlust. 

TL;DR - went to a theme park outside of Tokyo and had a fantastic time. Nicky likes traveling now.

Tokyo dump…

1 - arriving at Shinjuku Station after 24 hours no sleep and the airline losing our luggage. We barely made it on the last train out of Narita. It was Lost in Translation meets the Terminal right off the bat but we made it. 

2 - Our Airbnb in Yamabukicho. 2 stories, 2 private bedrooms and really convenient access to subway at Edogawabashi station. We rode the subway like champion peasants the entire time we were in Tokyo. So efficient. 

3 - Electric City in Akihabara. Crazy place with 10-story arcades, electronic stores and anime shops galore. My kid decided it was the perfect time to start a figurine collection and fleeced me out of a paycheck to start his. 

3 - A Maid Cafe in Akihabara. They wear maid outfits, call you master and make you do silly things while they draw on your food. This would never happen in America. 

4-5 - Being tourists on these streets. Had to take a couple of basic pictures for our moms. 😂

6 - Don Quixote - basically the Walmart of Japan and a place to buy anything from random sex toys and poop caps to fresh undies for when the airline loses your luggage.

7-8 - Kabukicho entertainment district. Food, drink and all manor of tomfoolery and ballyhoo to be had here. 

9 - The famous Godzilla head on top of the movie theater in Kabukicho.

10 - Sensoji temple in Asakusa. This place’s history extends past 1,000 years. They had some interesting street food nearby as well, of which we had plenty. Green teas, taiyaki and chicken karaage - smashed! Takoyaki and those sweet rice ball things - pass next time!

That’s all for this one. Back to Manila tomorrow for a few more days then onward to reality and writing a new and amazing future. LFG.

FB memory from 6 years ago today. Me and @cyriljeff were stuck in Vegas after Masters Worlds when Houston got hit with Hurricane Harvey. Unable to get back to Houston, I felt horrible about not being able to physically help. Especially after seeing guys like Derrick Lewis riding around and helping others in his big ole truck. After finally getting back I immediately decided to raise money and put together an auction together with @sethdanielsf2w and @f2wbjj. Everyone pitched in from @lucaatalla @renzograciebii and @gordonlovesjiujitsu to instructors/brands/individuals all around the world. We ended up raising around 60k, all of which I personally hand delivered to actual victims and their families. To this day it remains one of the coolest things I’ve ever done and I’m forever proud of it. 🤘🏽

Moral of the Story - help others when you can, how you can, and just generally do your best to be a good person. You’ll appreciate it later!

Craziest height disparity I’ve ever shot as far as #mma goes. I miss the OG Legacy Fighting days with @mickmaynard2. Golden era of MMA for me where I’d drive everywhere every weekend and write a few articles every day just to give adequate media coverage to the Texas MMA Scene back when there was practically nobody else that did.

We’ve all moved on since then and Mick sold Legacy and got hired as UFC matchmaker which was announced on the second slide press release 7 years ago today. (Happy work anniversary btw!) 

Nowadays we own an academy together (@renzogracielakehouston) where @lesterbeast1 is training future generations of MMA and UFC fighters but those early days covering, promoting and fighting in Houston were pretty damn cool.

#mma #houstonmma #txmma #legacyfighting

When it comes to innovative submissions, the “Rexangle” remains one of the most unique ones I’ve ever seen. More impressive yet, former Legacy FC champ and now tenured TDLR referee Jeff Rexroad was able to hit the submission in big fights. Probably 1,000s of grappling matches and MMA fights since and I still haven’t seen anyone replicate it.

Check out Rich Burmaster’s (@shonuffstuff) YouTube or just search “Rexangle breakdown” and you’ll see an old school breakdown of how he sets this up and hits up. It’s worth a watch. 

#og #mma #houstonmma #legacyfights
